    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras face a challenging slate today as we navigate a series of matchups against several high-tier arms, including Sale and Bradish. Our strongest play by a significant margin is **Yordan Alvarez** (82.97), who benefits from a favorable matchup against Gil (5.74 xERA). The projection model heavily favors **Yordan Alvarez** due to his elite xwOBA and a generous 19% SP skill boost, making him our primary anchor for HR and RBI production. **Junior Caminero** (71.00) also projects as an elite start; he draws a soft matchup against Woods Richardson and gains significant value from a prime #2 spot in the order, effectively offsetting the park factor drag. \n\nWhile we are hunting for production, we remain hyper-aware of our scarcity needs in stolen bases. **Victor Scott II** (53.24) and **Caleb Durbin** (47.66) remain in the lineup despite marginal efficiency scores because of their speed profiles. **Caleb Durbin** receives a notable 16% park boost against Bradish, which pushes his utility above our bench candidates. The most difficult bench decision involved **Carson Benge** (44.06); while his profile is solid, his status remains \"Lineup Pending,\" and the combination of wind-in and a lower-order projection saw him edged out by the higher-floor consistency of **Kazuma Okamoto** (55.27).\n\nCaution is advised regarding our middle-infield stack. **Trea Turner** (54.65) and **Kyle Schwarber** (52.96) face Sale, whose 2.88 xERA is the most daunting obstacle on today\u2019s board. While both players possess the talent to break a slate regardless of the matchup, their efficiency is depressed by the SP skill penalty. We are also monitoring **Hyeseong Kim** (46.77); while he benefits from a wind-out scenario against Imanaga, his platoon disadvantage remains a risk. We are keeping **Pete Crow-Armstrong** and **Chase Meidroth** on standby, but given today's SP landscape, we are prioritizing power-heavy matchups to ensure we don't bleed too much in the AVG and HR categories.",
